<TITLE> Eleven killed in landmine blast in Chhattisgarh </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 RAIPUR, India, Wed May 6, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Eleven people, including seven policemen, were killed on Wednesday in a landmine attack by Maoists in Chhattisgarh, police said. Maoist rebels, who say they are fighting for the rights of poor farmers and landless labourers, had stepped up violent attacks ahead of the month-long general election which winds down next week and ordered people to boycott the polls. The blast, in a forested stretch of Dantewada district's Injeram area, about 500 km (310 miles) south of capital Raipur, also wounded two people, said Pawan Deo, deputy inspector general. "The policemen were travelling in a tractor trolley when the insurgents blew it up with a landmine," Deo said. The attack occurred a day after Maoists shot dead a leader of the state's ruling Bharatiya Janata Party. Thousands have been killed in the Maoist insurgency which began in the late 1960s, and which Prime Minister Manmohan Singh has described as one of the gravest threats to India's internal security. About 1,500 have been killed in Chhattisgarh alone since the state was formed in 
